\pard\f0\fs28 {\i D. cintranus} auct., non Boiss. & Reuter,{\i  D. marizii} (Samp.) Samp.). Laxly caespitose perennial, woody at base; stems 20-60 cm. Basal leaves 10-30 mm, linear-subulate, fasciculate, with a distinct mid-vein and prominent marginal veins, erect and somewhat rigid; cauline leaves 4-6 pairs, erect. Flowers often 2 or 3 together. Epicalyx segments 4(-6), ovate, whitish, not veined, all more or less abruptly cuspidate with a green point, c. 1/3 as long as calyx. Calyx 14-20 × 4-5 mm, narrowed above; teeth acute, mucronulate. Petal-limb 5-10 mm, bright reddish-purple to pale pink. •{\i  C. & W. Spain, N. & C. Portugal}. Hs Lu.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 A very variable species variously divided into a number of subspecies and species by different authors.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 72. D. serratifolius }Sm. in Sibth. & Sm., {\i Fl. Graec. Prodr.}{\b 1}: 287 (1809). Laxly to rather densely caespitose perennial 15-30 cm, with long, trailing, woody stems. Basal leaves usually 15-30 mm, linear, acuminate, with 3 prominent veins beneath; cauline smaller. Flowers usually solitary. Epicalyx-scales elliptical or ovate, acute or acuminate, usually entirely brown. Calyx 9-15 × c. 3 mm, tapering from near base, becoming cylindrical in fruit. Petal-limb 3-4 mm, dentate, pink.{\i  S. & E.C. Greece.} Gr.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 The plants from the mountains of S. Greece (Peloponnisos) have somewhat shorter basal leaves, fewer cauline leaves, (2-)4 somewhat longer epicalyx-scales, and a more deeply dentate petal-limb. They have been called subsp. {\b abbreviatus} (Heldr. & Halácsy) Strid,{\i  Mount. Fl. Gr.}{\b  1}: 179 (1986).
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 73. D. pyrenaicus }Pourret, {\i Mém. Acad. Sci. Toulouse}{\b  3}: 318 (1788) ({\i D. attenuatus} Sm.,{\i  D. requienii} sensu Willk. pro parte, non Gren. & Godron,{\i  D. maritimus} Rouy). Laxly caespitose perennial 15-45 cm, usually with long, trailing, rather slender, woody stems. Leaves usually rigid, pungent, not densely crowded on flowering stems. Inflorescence usually branched. Epicalyx-scales (4-)6-8, ovate, gradually acuminate, c. 1/3 as long as calyx. Calyx 15-30 × 2-3 mm, tapering markedly from about the middle. Petal-limb 3-8 mm, glabrous, dentate, pink. 2n = 30, 60. •{\i  S. France, N.E. Spain.} Ga Hs.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b pyrenaicus}: Not glaucous. Calyx 15-20 mm. Petal-limb c. 3 mm, pale pink.{\i  Pyrenees}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b catalaunicus} (Willk. & Costa) Tutin,{\i  Feddes Repert.}{\b  68}: 190 (1963). Usually glaucous. Calyx 20-30 mm. Petal-limb 6-8 mm, deep pink.{\i  Throughout the range of the species.}
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 74. D. lusitanus }Brot., {\i Fl. Lusit.}{\b  2}: 177 (1804) ({\i D. lusitanicus} auct.). Glaucous perennial 15-45 cm; stems erect or ascending, woody below. Leaves usually c. 10 mm, not crowded on flowering stems, somewhat fleshy and without obvious veins. Inflorescence usually branched. Epicalyx-scales 4, ovate, acuminate, c. 1/3 as long as calyx. Calyx 20-23 × 2·5-3·5 mm, tapering markedly from about the middle. Petal-limb 7-10 mm, bearded, deeply dentate, pink. 2n = 30, 60.{\i  Spain and Portugal.} Hs Lu.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 75. D. serrulatus }Desf.,{\i  Fl. Atl. }{\b 1}: 346 (1798) ({\i D. malacitanus} Haenseler ex Boiss., nom. inval.,{\i  D. broteri} Boiss. & Reuter,{\i  D. valentinus} Willk., {\i D. fimbriatus} Brot., non Bieb.). Perennial up to 50 cm. Leaves 1-2 mm wide, linear, acuminate, glaucous. Epicalyx-scales usually 6-8, elliptical to ovate-lanceolate, acuminate, 1/3-1/2 as long as calyx. Calyx c. 30 mm, tapering from near base. Petal-limb c. 15 mm, laciniate, bearded. 2n = 60.{\i  S. & E. Spain, S. & C. Portugal}. Hs Lu.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28 European plants are referable to subsp. {\b barbatus} (Boiss.) Greuter & Burdet,{\i  Willdenowia}{\b  13}: 281 (1984). Subsp. {\b serrulatus} occurs in N.W. Africa.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 76. D. scaber }Chaix in Vill.,{\i  Hist. Pl. Dauph.}{\b  1}: 331 (1786) ({\i D. hirtus} Vill.). Laxly caespitose perennial 15-40 cm. Leaves 1-3 mm wide, flat, linear, acuminate; cauline leaves usually 3 or 4 pairs. Flowers in small heads; bracts usually absent. Epicalyx-scales usually 6, ovate, acuminate, from ½ as long as to as long as calyx. Calyx 17-22(-25) mm, tapering above the middle. Petal-limb 4-8 mm, dentate, bearded. •{\i  S.W. Europe.} Ga Hs Lu.
